The data points aggregate around two trends. For defects with |Et| < 0.1 eV, the classification accuracy drops to 68.7%, which still provides a decent indication regarding the half bandgap location without the need for additional measurements. As previously discussed for Fig. 2, defects with Et near the mid-gap are harder to differentiate for both human and ML. Outside the mid-gap range (|Et| > 0.1 eV), the NN classification model performs extremely well, with a 94.7% half bandgap location classification accuracy. The second trend is that outside the mid-gap region, the most incorrect classification is for defects with k values around 0.83 ± 0.01, represented by the dotted black line in Fig. 5. This corresponds to the ratio between hole and electron thermal velocity. Indeed, when the value k approaches vp/vn, it equalizes τn0 and τp0, resulting in the following simplified SRH equation:1τSRH=τn0⋅1+p1+n1+Δnp0+n0+Δn\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
